Have a look at com.atlassian.core.util.FileUtils#deleteDir method and the way it's handling a symbolic link.

We should throw an exception instead of returning false.

This way if somebody is using a symbolic link, the user will know the problem immediately instead of some mysterious behaviour occurring in Confluence. This is because Confluence is not yet able to work with symbolic link. See [this doc|http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/DOC/Confluence%20Data%20Directory%20Configuration].

Typical problems that will arise when using symbolic link eg. for /temp folder is:
- Download path is changed, causing users unable to download data exports of any kind despite that the exports have been created successfully.
- Confluence cannot delete files from /temp eg.
{noformat}
2009-12-29 04:00:00,416 ERROR [DefaultQuartzScheduler_Worker-2] [confluence.importexport.impl.CleanTempDirectoryJob] executeJob Failed to delete /broad/srv/confluence/main/data/temp/xmlexport-20091228-174839-11
{noformat}

The wiki markup:

{code}
{section}
{recently-updated}
{section}
{code}

Will mangle the recently updated output (see: broken.jpg)

Adding \{column} tags within the section like so:

{code}
{section}
{column}
{recently-updated}
{column}
{section}
{code}

...will fix the problem (see: fixed.jpg).

As far as I can tell this only affects Firefox, Safari IE7 and Chrome were unaffected. Couldn't replicate in 3.0.2.

I am using this code fragment in the wiki markup editor to display some stuff such as diagrams and text boxes at the right side:
{noformat}
{html}
<div style="float:right">
{html}

here is my stuff

{html}</div>{html}
{noformat}

After switching to the wysiwyg editor and then back to the wiki markup editor the code has been changed to:

{noformat}
{html}
<DIV mce_style="float:right" style="float: right;">
</DIV><P mce_style="display:none" style="display: none;" user="true"><BR></BR></P>
<P>here is my stuff</P>
<P mce_style="display:none" style="display: none;" user="true"><BR></BR></P>
<DIV class="wysiwyg-macro" macrohasbody="true" macroname="html" macrostarttag="{html}" 
wikihasnewlineafterbody="false" wikihasnewlinebeforebody="false" wikihasprecedingnewline="true" wikihastrailingnewline="false"></DIV>
{html}
{noformat}

The HTML code no longer works after this modification.

My expectation is that whatever I enter between the \{html\} tags is not modified by Confluence. It is, after all, arbitrary HTML code.
